column1: Who will President Biden announce as his choice to replace Justice Breyer on the US Supreme Court?
column5: ['J. Michelle Childs', 'Anita Earls', 'Ketanji Brown Jackson', 'Candace Jackson-Akiwumi', 'Leondra Kruger', 'Melissa Murray', 'Wilhelmina Wright', 'Someone else', 'Biden will not announce a choice before 1 July 2022']

column6: After my last forecast, I learned Jackson's releasing opinions early. Good signal.
KBJ up 15%. While vetted in the past, I'm sure the opo mills are in high gear so nothing can be ruled out.

I think Ketanji Brown Jackson will be Biden's nominee. - She's the right age. - Paul Ryan has spoken highly of her. - She's being endorsed by many groups. - She clerked for Justice Breyer - She is highly accomplished.
KBJ up 10%; someone else down the same. The latter is not getting much public traction.
Looking at number of recent wiki edits, and basically zero extra knowledge about nomination.
I'm going with the crowd here as I know nothing about the subject, but kind of interested :)

I believe that the priority is to get a bipartisan vote. Graham has indicated Childs and Clyburn is pushing for her. I also think that not going to an Ivy league school will end up as an asset to be able to say that she looks more like "America," a quote from Graham about her being African American. So I'm flipping my forecast in her favor.

brown jackson has been on short lists for quite a while and she is still fairly young and has the right experience. Childs may make confirmation easier but she is older and less experienced. Kruger would be my dark horse as the youngest.
Initial forecast. Wonder if D poobahs are angling for the VP to upscale her CV?
Ballpark estimate. Refining and research to come. Informed by crowd consensus, past accuracy of predictions on this matter, and PredictIt trends.

Biden will likely pick a nominee based on merit, leading me to favor Jackson, as the DC Circuit is the most prominent circuit due to its jurisdiction. Next on merit would be Kruger from the CA Supreme Court. If politics plays any role, my vote goes to Earls, which may translate to a Democratic win in NC in 24. (I realize Childs has been in the news a lot lately.) Wild card: Biden nominates VP Kamala Harris, former attorney general of CA. Would then open the door to the most electable Dem in 24 being nominated as VP and having a national position to assist their run.
age issues and Sen. Clyburn "Trumps" all others
